1fd", "default": false, "description": "Category: This is a bug."}], "state": "closed", "locked": false, "assignee": null, "assignees": [], "milestone": null, "comments": 6, "created_at": "2017-05-23T15:20:24Z", "updated_at": "2023-03-21T06:00:18Z", "closed_at": "2023-03-21T06:00:17Z", "author_association": "NONE", "active_lock_reason": null, "body": "`std::net::Ipv6Addr::to_ipv4` maps `::1` to an invalid IP (`0.0.0.1`)\r\n\r\nI tried this code to make a very simple and crude IP filter (sufficient for my use case):\r\n\r\n```rust\r\nmatch\r\n    match remote.ip() { // IP from web framework\r\n        IpAddr::V4(ipv4) => Some(ipv4.octets()),\r\n        IpAddr::V6(ipv6) => ipv6.to_ipv4().map(|ipv4| ipv4.octets())\r\n    } {\r\n        // ... other cases\r\n        Some([127, 0, 0, _]) => {},\r\n        x => {\r\n            debug!(\"Invalid IP: {:?}\", x);\r\n            return Err(...);\r\n        },\r\n}\r\n```\r\n\r\nI expected to see this happen:\r\n\r\nI expected `std::net::Ipv6Addr::to_ipv4` to return something like `Some(127.0.0.1)` for `::1` or at least `None`, because you could argue, that `::1` is not strictly the same as `127.0.0.1`, but then again loopback is loopback.\r\n\r\nInstead, this happened:\r\n\r\nBut I did really not expect to get returned an **invalid** IPv4 address, which is why I consider this a bug, that has cost me far too much time.\r\n\r\n## Meta\r\n\r\n`rustc --version --verbose`:\r\n\r\n```\r\nrustc 1.19.0-nightly (81734e0e0 2017-05-22)\r\nbinary: rustc\r\ncommit-hash: 81734e0e06d24cf580dd5352c64d10110e4d3b7b\r\ncommit-date: 2017-05-22\r\nhost: x86_64-unknown-linux-gnu\r\nrelease: 1.19.0-nightly\r\nLLVM version: 4.0\r\n```", "closed_by": {"login": "Dylan-DPC", "id": 99973273, "node_id": "U_kgDOBfV4mQ", "avatar_url": "https://avatars.githubusercontent.com/u/99973273?v=4", "gravatar_id": "", "url": "https://api.github.com/users/Dylan-DPC", "html_url": "https://github.com/Dylan-DPC", "followers_url": "https://api.github.com/users/Dylan-DPC/